### Description

When an `EnvironmentInjector` is created with `createEnvironmentInjector(providers, application.injector)`, calling `application.destroy()` does not destroy that child injector.

This is surprising because services provided by the child injector can use `DestroyRef.onDestroy()` for cleanup, but those callbacks never run unless the child injector is destroyed manually.

This can leave async work such as timers, polling, backend requests, or delayed callbacks alive after the application is destroyed. Later, that async logic may attempt to inject dependencies from the already-destroyed application/root injector and receiving NG0205 error.

```typescript
import {createEnvironmentInjector, provideZonelessChangeDetection} from '@angular/core';
import {createApplication} from '@angular/platform-browser';

it(`should destroy environment injector`, async () => {
    const application = await createApplication({
        providers: [provideZonelessChangeDetection()],
    });

    const injector = createEnvironmentInjector([], application.injector);

    application.destroy();

    expect(injector.destroyed).toBe(true); // actually false
});
```


